export const PRODUCT = {

omniscripts: {
  packages: ['omnistudio'],
  name: "OmniScripts",
  icon: "\u{1FA84}",
  color: "#a78bfa",
  description: "The heart of OmniStudio's guided experience framework. OmniScripts let you build multi-step, guided processes that walk users through complex workflows without writing code. The visual designer provides a drag-and-drop canvas where you compose steps from a rich palette of input elements, display elements, and server-side actions. Each OmniScript compiles into an optimized Lightning Web Component for production performance, with versioning and activation controls for safe iteration. OmniScripts support session persistence for long-running processes, enabling users to save progress and resume later. They can be embedded in Lightning pages, Experience Cloud sites, or invoked by Agentforce actions.",
  components: [
    {id:"os-designer",name:"OmniScript Designer",icon:"\u{1F3A8}",desc:"The visual canvas for building guided processes. Administrators drag elements from the palette onto steps, configure properties, and wire up data bindings and actions. The standard designer provides instant activation, drag-and-drop that is twice as fast as the managed package designer, and Omniscript activation up to six times faster. Real-time preview with JSON data inspection lets you test each step independently, and a component tree helps navigate complex scripts with up to 750 elements.",tags:["OmniProcess","OmniProcessElement"],docs:["OmniScripts are created with a unique combination of Type, SubType, and Language that together become the compiled component's name. The Type and SubType can only contain letters and numbers without spaces or underscores, and the combined length must not exceed 60 characters. For example, Type=account and SubType=Create with Language=English generates a component named accountCreateEnglish. The designer supports two modes: the standard designer (recommended for new implementations) and the managed package designer, though components edited in the standard designer cannot be opened in the managed package designer afterward.","The standard designer offers a streamlined experience where you drag elements directly onto the canvas and edit their properties simultaneously without switching between tabs. The element palette includes groups, Data Mapper actions, standard actions, display elements, functions, inputs, and embedded OmniScripts. Steps define the top-level pages, and within steps you can add any element. Action and OmniScript elements can be placed directly on the canvas outside of steps, while all other elements must reside inside a step or action block.","Multi-language support enables a single OmniScript to run in multiple languages through Salesforce custom labels. Translation Workbench must be enabled first, and you define custom label translations for each element property that needs localization. The system provides autotranslated system labels for single-language OmniScripts based on the user's locale. Date and time pickers can also be localized using JSON-format custom labels derived from the Day.js locale library.","When working with multiple developers, always create a new version of an OmniScript before making changes to avoid property set conflicts. Version management lets teams maintain multiple versions with clear active and inactive states. Activation compiles the OmniScript definition and locks the design, and deactivation reverts to the previous active version automatically."],connections:[{planet:"flexcards",desc:"OmniScripts launch FlexCards as embedded displays"},{planet:"integration",desc:"OmniScripts invoke Integration Procedures for server-side logic"},{planet:"datamappers",desc:"OmniScripts use Data Mappers for data read and write operations"},{planet:"formulas",desc:"OmniScripts evaluate formula expressions in SetValues and calculations"},{planet:"lwc",desc:"OmniScripts host custom LWC elements in the designer palette"}]},
    {id:"os-input-elements",name:"Input Elements",icon:"\u{1F4DD}",desc:"Eighteen input types for collecting user data within guided processes. Includes Text, Number, Currency, Date, Time, Email, URL, Telephone, Password, TextArea, Select, Multi-Select, Lookup, Checkbox, Radio, Range, File Upload, and Signature Capture. Each input supports validation rules, conditional visibility, default values, and data binding to the OmniScript JSON data model. Select, Multi-Select, and Radio options can be populated manually, from Salesforce picklist fields, or programmatically through Apex classes.",tags:["OmniProcessElement"],docs:["Input elements are the primary way users interact with OmniScripts. Each element automatically writes its value to the OmniScript JSON data model using its name as the key, making the data immediately available to other elements and actions. Default values can be set statically through the properties panel, or dynamically by pre-filling from a Data Mapper Extract or JSON response. When a user fills in an element, the default value is overwritten.","Validation runs automatically when a user clicks out of a field. To enable real-time validation as users type, set the commitOnChange property to true in the JSON editor. Each input supports minimum and maximum value constraints, required field enforcement, pattern matching via masks, and custom error messages. The Conditional View property lets you show, hide, or make an element required based on data values from other elements.","Select, Multi-Select, and Radio elements offer three option sources: manual entry of label-value pairs in the designer, Salesforce object picklist fields using sObject.fieldName syntax, or custom Apex class methods that return options programmatically. Dependent Select elements can be configured with a controlling field that dynamically filters available options based on another element's value. For multi-language OmniScripts, option labels are resolved through custom labels.","The Lookup element lets users search Salesforce data by typing text, which triggers a query and returns results as selectable options in a dropdown. File and Image elements handle uploads with details stored in the Files node of the data JSON. The Range element presents a slider for numeric input with configurable increments, and the Signature Capture element collects handwritten signatures directly within the guided process."],connections:[]},
    {id:"os-display-elements",name:"Display & Formula Elements",icon:"\u{1F4CA}",desc:"Elements for presenting computed data and controlling layout within steps. Disclosure elements create collapsible sections, Formula elements evaluate expressions in real-time, Aggregate elements summarize data across repeatable blocks, and SetValues elements perform silent data transformations in the background. The Messaging element displays comments, requirements, and success or warning messages based on whether a validation expression evaluates to true or false, providing immediate feedback to users.",tags:["OmniProcessElement"],docs:["Formula and Aggregate elements create expressions that calculate values and evaluate data across multiple fields. They support merge fields referencing other elements (wrapped in percent signs), numbers, string literals, booleans, arrays, dates, and null values. Formula elements can use all supported operators (addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, power, comparisons, and logical operators) along with the full OmniScript function library. Aggregate elements are specifically designed for operations on repeatable data, such as averaging or summing values from Edit Block rows.","The Messaging element displays contextual messages based on validation results. After creating a Formula or Aggregate element, you configure a Messaging element with a validation expression that evaluates to true or false, then define different message types and content for each outcome. Merge fields are supported in message text, and messaging can be configured at different severity levels including comments, requirements, success, and warnings.","Text Block elements present rich text content within steps using either the TinyMCE or Lightning Rich Text Editor. The TinyMCE editor supports fonts in points, field references in curly brace format, custom styles, and paragraph-level CSS classes. The Lightning Rich Text Editor supports custom labels in the format Label.customLabelName. You can switch between editors by enabling the EnableLightningRTE interaction configuration setting.","The Conditional View property on display elements controls visibility based on data values. Show if True renders the element only when conditions are met, Disable Read Only if True toggles editability, and Set to Required if True makes fields mandatory based on conditions. Conditions support AND and OR logical operators, and can reference values from other elements using merge field syntax. When an element is hidden, its value in the data JSON is set to null."],connections:[{planet:"formulas",desc:"Display elements use formula functions for computed values"}]},
    {id:"os-action-elements",name:"Action Elements",icon:"\u{26A1}",desc:"Server-side operation elements that connect OmniScripts to backend systems. Integration Procedure Actions invoke IP flows, Data Mapper Actions read and write Salesforce data, Remote Actions call Apex classes implementing the Callable interface, HTTP Actions make REST callouts, Email Actions send templated messages, DocuSign Actions trigger e-signature workflows, and Navigate Actions redirect users on completion. Actions can execute on step entry, step exit, or user click, and each supports custom error messages with configurable failure behavior.",tags:["OmniProcessElement","OmniProcess"],docs:["OmniScript action elements form the bridge between the user interface and backend data operations. Data Mapper Extract and Turbo Extract actions query Salesforce data using pre-configured Data Mapper definitions, while Data Mapper Post actions write collected data back to Salesforce objects. Integration Procedure actions invoke server-side orchestration flows that can chain multiple data operations, callouts, and business logic into a single execution. Each action element has properties for error handling, including custom error messages, failure navigation labels, and in-progress messaging.","Remote Actions call Apex classes that implement the Callable interface (or the legacy VlocityOpenInterface). You specify the class name, method name, and any additional input parameters. HTTP Actions make direct REST callouts to external APIs with configurable headers, authentication, and response mapping. Both action types extend the OmniScript's reach beyond Salesforce data into third-party integrations and custom business logic.","DocuSign integration requires an active DocuSign account with OAuth 2.0 Named Credentials configured in Salesforce. The DocuSign Envelope Action sends documents for signature, and the DocuSign Signature Action embeds the signing ceremony inline within the OmniScript. Templates are fetched from DocuSign through the OmniStudio DocuSign Setup page, and field mapping is handled through Data Mapper Transforms that map OmniScript data to DocuSign template custom fields. Send-on-behalf functionality allows multiple users to initiate signing workflows through a shared credential.","Navigate Actions redirect users after completing a process, supporting record pages, Experience Cloud pages, external URLs, and custom Lightning components. Email Actions send templated notifications through Salesforce email services. Actions can be grouped in Action Blocks, which execute multiple actions as a single unit, though some actions (DocuSign Signature, Navigate, PDF, Set Errors, and Set Values) cannot be placed in Action Blocks."],connections:[{planet:"integration",desc:"Action elements execute Integration Procedures"},{planet:"datamappers",desc:"Action elements invoke Data Mapper operations"},{planet:"config",desc:"Action elements reference e-signature and interaction configurations"}]},
    {id:"os-groups",name:"Step & Group Elements",icon:"\u{1F4C2}",desc:"Structural elements for organizing OmniScript content. Steps define the top-level pages in a guided process with navigation controls including customizable Next, Previous, Save, and Cancel labels. Edit Blocks create repeatable groups of elements for collecting list data with add, edit, and delete operations. Action Blocks group up to ten actions into a single execution unit. The recommended limit is 750 total elements, 20 child OmniScripts, and 10 nested blocks per OmniScript.",tags:["OmniProcessElement"],docs:["Steps are the primary structural element and define individual pages in a guided process. Each step supports custom navigation labels for Next, Previous, Save, and Cancel buttons, and can display a save confirmation message when users save their progress. Steps can be conditionally shown or hidden based on data values, enabling dynamic branching where the process adjusts its path based on user choices. A step's conditional visibility is controlled through the Show Element if True property with AND or OR logic across multiple conditions.","Edit Blocks create repeatable sections where users can add, modify, or delete rows of data. This is ideal for collecting list information such as multiple family members, line items, or contact details. Edit Blocks support custom labels for the Add New, Edit, and Delete buttons. Data from Edit Blocks is stored as arrays in the OmniScript JSON data model, and Formula or Aggregate elements can reference these arrays for calculations like SUM, AVERAGE, COUNT, MIN, and MAX across all rows.","Action Blocks group multiple action elements for sequential execution, limited to four action types: Data Mapper Extract, Data Mapper Post, Integration Procedure, and Remote actions. The recommended limit is 10 Action Blocks per OmniScript. Conditional Actions (up to 20 recommended) can be configured to execute based on data conditions, allowing different actions to fire depending on user inputs or data states.","OmniScripts can embed other OmniScripts as child components for modular reuse. The recommended limit is 20 child OmniScripts per parent. Embedded OmniScripts share data context with the parent and can be referenced using the Type/SubType/Language key. Custom styling can be applied through static resources, global stylesheets, or SLDS design tokens, with support for Newport and Lightning themes in the designer canvas."],connections:[]},
    {id:"os-sessions",name:"Saved Sessions & Resume",icon:"\u{1F4BE}",desc:"Session persistence for long-running guided processes. When enabled, OmniScripts automatically save user progress so they can close the browser and resume later from exactly where they left off. Saved sessions capture the full JSON data model state, the current step position, and any uploaded files. Session data is stored in Omniscript Saved Session records that track the user, save timestamp, last saved page, and expiration date.",tags:["OmniscriptSavedSession","OmniProcessTransientData"],docs:["Saved sessions allow users to pause a guided process at any point and return later to complete it. When a user clicks Save for Later, the OmniScript serializes all entered data, the current step position, and file uploads into a Saved Session record linked to the user. The session status tracks the lifecycle: In Progress for active sessions, Resumed when a user returns, and Completed when the process finishes. Administrators can set expiration dates after which sessions are no longer resumable.","Transient Data records provide a separate mechanism for storing intermediate data during long-running processes that span multiple server requests or require asynchronous processing. Unlike Saved Sessions which are user-initiated, Transient Data is managed by the system to maintain state between execution steps. Each record has an expiration date and a status (Active, Consumed, or Expired), and records are automatically purged after expiration.","Session persistence settings are configured through the OmniScript properties and Interaction Configuration. Administrators can control whether the Save button appears on each step, configure auto-save intervals for processes where data loss would be costly, and set up resume URLs that direct users back to their in-progress OmniScripts. The resume capability works across Lightning pages and Experience Cloud sites, though the user must authenticate to access their saved session."],connections:[]},
    {id:"os-compilation",name:"Activation & Compilation",icon:"\u{2699}",desc:"Compiles OmniScript definitions into optimized Lightning Web Component bundles for production execution. With the standard designer, activation is instant and up to six times faster than the managed package designer. Activation locks the design and validates all element references and data bindings, catching errors before deployment. Version management supports multiple versions with a dedicated Manage Versions page for comparing changes between iterations.",tags:["OmniProcessCompilation","OmniProcess"],docs:["When you activate an OmniScript, the platform pre-compiles all element configurations, merge fields, and data mappings into a single optimized payload stored in an Omni Process Compilation record. This compiled form is loaded at runtime to avoid re-processing the element tree on every execution, resulting in significantly faster load times for end users. If an error occurs during activation, the OmniScript is automatically deactivated to prevent broken experiences.","With the standard designer and standard runtime (Managed Package Runtime disabled), activation no longer generates a separate Lightning Web Component. Instead, the compiled content runs through standard Omniscript and Flexcard components available in Lightning App Builder and Experience Builder. This eliminates the LWC generation step and enables instant activation. For Experience Cloud LWR sites, you can use the Load Omniscript from URL option instead of a dedicated component.","Active OmniScripts can be launched in several ways: as a URL link, embedded on Lightning pages through the standard component, placed on Experience Cloud pages for customer-facing portals, or invoked from FlexCard actions. In the standard designer, the How to Launch dialog provides the URL for direct linking. When using the managed package runtime, compiled OmniScripts can also be launched as standalone Lightning Web Components or embedded in other LWCs.","Version management tracks all iterations of an OmniScript with numbered versions. Only one version can be active at a time for a given Type, SubType, and Language combination. Deactivating the current version automatically falls back to no active version. The standard designer provides a dedicated Manage Versions page that makes it easy to compare versions and switch between them. Always create a new version before opening an existing OmniScript in the standard designer for the first time, as components edited in the standard designer cannot be opened in the managed package designer afterward."],connections:[{planet:"deployment",desc:"Compiled OmniScripts are packaged in DataPacks for migration"},{planet:"testing",desc:"Compiled OmniScripts are validated in preview and test frameworks"}]}
  ],
  dataFlow:["Designer assembles steps with input, display, and action elements","User launches the OmniScript and navigates through steps","Input elements collect data into the JSON data model","Action elements invoke Integration Procedures and Data Mappers","Completion triggers final save, navigation, or downstream processes"],
  connections:[{planet:"flexcards",desc:"OmniScripts embed FlexCards for data display"},{planet:"integration",desc:"OmniScripts invoke Integration Procedures for server logic"},{planet:"datamappers",desc:"OmniScripts call Data Mappers for data read/write"},{planet:"formulas",desc:"OmniScripts use formula functions in calculations"},{planet:"analytics",desc:"OmniScript interactions are tracked for analytics"},{planet:"testing",desc:"OmniScripts are validated in preview and test tools"},{planet:"agentforce",desc:"OmniScripts are exposed as Agentforce actions"},{planet:"experience",desc:"OmniScripts are embedded in Experience Cloud pages"},{planet:"config",desc:"OmniScripts read interaction configuration settings"},{planet:"deployment",desc:"OmniScripts are exported via DataPacks"},{planet:"lwc",desc:"OmniScripts host custom LWC elements"}]
},

flexcards: {
  packages: ['omnistudio'],
  name: "FlexCards",
  icon: "\u{1F5C2}",
  color: "#f472b6",
  description: "A declarative UI framework for building contextual data cards that surface the right information at the right time. FlexCards pull data from multiple sources and render it in compact, visually rich card layouts with conditional states and interactive actions. The visual designer lets you compose card layouts without code, bind data from Integration Procedures, SOQL queries, Apex, or REST APIs, and define multiple card states that switch based on data conditions. FlexCards can launch OmniScripts, navigate to records, or open flyout panels. They support nesting through child cards, enabling modular and reusable UI compositions across Lightning pages and Experience Cloud sites.",
  components: [
    {id:"fc-designer",name:"FlexCard Designer",icon:"\u{1F3A8}",desc:"The visual editor for building card layouts and managing card states. The standard designer lets you drag elements to the canvas and edit properties simultaneously without switching tabs, with drag speed twice as fast and activation up to seven times faster than the managed package designer. A real-time preview shows how the card renders with live data, and a 12-column responsive grid controls element layout across different device sizes.",tags:["OmniUiCard"],docs:["FlexCards are created with a unique combination of Name and Author. Names can only contain letters, numbers, and underscores, must begin with a letter, and cannot contain reserved words like Action, Flyout, or FlyoutType. The standard designer streamlines the creation process by letting you drag elements to the canvas and edit their properties in the same view, eliminating tab switching. Activation is up to seven times faster than the managed package designer.","The designer canvas uses a 12-column grid system for responsive layouts. Each element's width is set as a proportion of the grid (for example, 6 means 50% of available horizontal space). Turning on the Responsive toggle lets you set different widths for large, medium, small, and smaller viewports, so cards automatically adapt to desktops, tablets, and mobile devices. Heights are controlled through CSS values on the Style tab.","Style configuration is deeply integrated into the designer. You can set backgrounds, text properties, borders, dimensions, and spacing for individual elements, then save styles for reuse across multiple elements. Conditional styles change appearance based on data values (for example, adding a red border when a bill is past due). Custom CSS classes can be created in an inline code editor, and the generated CSS is saved as a Salesforce attachment that becomes part of the compiled component package.","FlexCards support the recommended limit of 7 child FlexCards, 3 child OmniScripts, 20 Data Mappers, 20 Integration Procedures, 20 event listeners, and 10 versions per card. The Data Table element displays up to 750 rows. When preloading conditional components, all elements are added to the page DOM even when hidden, which can affect performance with large datasets. Disabling Preload Conditional Component for elements that are hidden by default reduces load time."],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"FlexCards launch OmniScripts from action buttons"},{planet:"integration",desc:"FlexCards invoke Integration Procedures as data sources"},{planet:"lwc",desc:"FlexCards embed custom LWC components for extended functionality"}]},
    {id:"fc-datasources",name:"Data Sources",icon:"\u{1F50C}",desc:"Connects FlexCards to backend data through multiple provider types. Integration Procedure data sources invoke server-side flows for complex data assembly. SOQL data sources run queries directly against Salesforce objects. Apex data sources call custom controller methods. REST data sources fetch from external APIs. Streaming API sources enable real-time card updates when underlying data changes, though Streaming API is supported at runtime but not in the standard designer.",tags:["OmniUiCard"],docs:["Data sources are the foundation of every FlexCard, providing the information that elements display to users. You configure a data source by selecting a provider type and specifying how the response fields map to card elements. The visual binding interface lets you select fields from the response or enter field names manually using curly brace syntax like {Type} or {AccountId}. Context variables pass dynamic values such as record IDs from the page to the data source at runtime.","For Salesforce data, SOQL data sources let you write queries directly in the designer, while Integration Procedure data sources are preferred for complex scenarios requiring multiple queries, data transformations, or external callouts. Apex data sources invoke custom controller methods for advanced logic that cannot be expressed declaratively. REST data sources connect to external APIs, and Streaming API data sources (supported at runtime in the managed package designer) enable real-time updates when underlying records change.","When a FlexCard uses an Integration Procedure as its data source, the IP runs on the server and returns assembled data that the card renders. This is the recommended pattern for production use cases because IPs support caching, error handling, and complex data assembly from multiple objects. For simple single-object queries during prototyping, SOQL data sources are faster to configure but lack the performance and reuse benefits of Integration Procedures.","FlexCards pass context to their data sources through context variables. On a record page, the record ID is automatically available. When a FlexCard is embedded in an OmniScript, it receives the OmniScript's data context. Child FlexCards receive data from their parent through the Parent.attr variable. The sample data source response field in the designer lets you provide mock JSON for previewing the card layout without live data connections."],connections:[{planet:"integration",desc:"Data sources invoke Integration Procedures for complex data assembly"},{planet:"datamappers",desc:"Data sources use Data Mappers for Salesforce data queries"}]},
    {id:"fc-states",name:"Card States & Conditions",icon:"\u{1F504}",desc:"Enables conditional rendering where a single FlexCard switches between different layouts based on data values. Each state defines its own element arrangement, styling, and actions, and condition logic determines which state is active. States are evaluated top to bottom, and the first matching state renders. A blank card state handles the scenario when the data source returns no records, ensuring the card always renders meaningful content.",tags:["OmniUiCard"],docs:["FlexCard states control what information and actions users see based on data conditions. When you create a FlexCard, it starts with a default state. You can add additional states with different element layouts, and each state has condition rules that determine when it displays. States are evaluated from top to bottom, and the first state whose conditions are met is rendered. The recommended practice is to arrange states from most specific to most general, ending with an unconditional default state and a blank card state for empty data.","Conditions can be applied at two levels: individual elements within a state, and the state itself. Element-level conditions show or hide specific fields, icons, or actions based on data values. State-level conditions switch the entire card layout. Both levels support comparison operators (equals, not equals, greater than, less than, contains) and can evaluate against data fields, empty values (using the keyword undefined), and context variables. Nested condition groups allow complex logic like [Priority = High AND IsEscalated = true] OR [Priority = High AND AnnualRevenue > 500000].","Private variables (using the Flex.varname syntax) enable dynamic interactions within a FlexCard at runtime. For example, you can create Show and Hide buttons that toggle a Flex.showinfo variable between true and false, with a block element conditioned to display only when the variable is true. Set Values actions on clickable elements update these variables, creating interactive expand/collapse patterns without any server calls.","For performance optimization, the Preload Conditional Component setting controls whether hidden elements are added to the page DOM. By default, all conditional elements are preloaded and hidden with CSS, which can slow load times for FlexCards with many conditional elements. Disabling preloading means hidden elements are not rendered at all until their conditions are met, which is recommended for data-heavy scenarios like case management dashboards with 100+ records."],connections:[]},
    {id:"fc-actions",name:"Actions & Flyouts",icon:"\u{1F3AF}",desc:"Interactive capabilities that make FlexCards actionable rather than purely informational. Actions can launch OmniScripts in modals or inline, navigate to record pages, Lightning apps, or Experience Cloud pages, and update field values or set private variables. Flyout panels open as modal or popover overlays containing additional FlexCards or OmniScripts, keeping users in context. A pubsub event system enables communication between FlexCards, including automatic flyout closure after task completion.",tags:["OmniUiCard","OmniProcess"],docs:["FlexCard actions transform cards from passive data displays into interactive interfaces. The OmniScript action type launches a guided process from the card, passing context data like the record ID so the OmniScript can pre-fill relevant information. For Experience Cloud sites, the Omniscript for Experience Builder component dynamically loads OmniScripts from FlexCard actions on a shared page, avoiding the need to create separate pages for each OmniScript. On LWR sites, the Load Omniscript from URL checkbox provides equivalent functionality.","Navigation actions support multiple target types: standard Salesforce apps (standard__appName), custom apps (namespace__appName), Lightning components, external URLs, and Experience Cloud pages. Input parameters can pass dynamic values using merge fields from the data source. The Update OmniScript action type writes data back to an OmniScript's JSON when the FlexCard is embedded within an OmniScript, enabling bidirectional communication between cards and guided processes.","Flyout panels create overlay experiences using modal dialogs or popover windows. A flyout can contain another FlexCard or an OmniScript, and the user can complete a task without leaving the current page context. Flyouts communicate with their parent FlexCard through a pubsub event channel. When a task completes in the flyout, publishing a close event on the channel automatically dismisses the flyout. The closemodal event with Composed and Bubbles properties provides an alternative for user-initiated modal dismissal.","Set Values actions update data fields or private variables (Flex.varname) without server calls, enabling interactive patterns like toggling visibility or updating display values in response to user clicks. Event listener actions respond to pubsub events from other components on the page. All actions support conditional visibility based on data field values, allowing different buttons and options to appear based on the record state."],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"Actions launch OmniScripts as modals or inline guided processes"},{planet:"agentforce",desc:"FlexCard actions integrate with Agentforce workflows"}]},
    {id:"fc-child-cards",name:"Child Cards & Embedding",icon:"\u{1F4E6}",desc:"Enables modular card composition through nesting. A parent FlexCard can embed up to 7 child FlexCards that receive data context from the parent through the Parent.attr context variable. Child cards can be repeated over list data, creating dynamic card grids. The recommended limit of 1 recursive FlexCard prevents infinite nesting. This composition pattern encourages building a library of small, focused cards that combine into rich contextual displays.",tags:["OmniUiCard"],docs:["Child FlexCards create a modular architecture where small, focused cards combine into complex data displays. A parent card can embed up to 7 child cards (recommended limit), and each child receives its parent's data context through the Parent.attr variable. When the parent card iterates over list data, each child card instance receives the data for one item in the list, creating repeatable card rows similar to a data grid but with the full visual flexibility of FlexCard design.","The ChildCardKeys field on the parent FlexCard definition stores comma-separated references to the child cards it embeds. Child cards have their own states and conditions, and can reference parent data in their condition expressions using the Parent.attr syntax. This allows a child card to adapt its layout based on both its own data and the parent context, enabling sophisticated multi-level conditional displays.","FlexCards are activated and published for use on Lightning pages and Experience Cloud sites. On Lightning pages, the FlexCard component is available in Lightning App Builder for drag-and-drop placement. On Experience Cloud sites, the same component works in Experience Builder for both Aura-based and LWR sites (though LWR sites require Managed Package Runtime enabled for Flexcard embedding using the generated LWC). The Interaction Access Configuration controls which interaction settings apply in portal environments.","Export and import of FlexCards follows the same pattern as other OmniStudio components. On the standard runtime, use Salesforce CLI for deployment between orgs. On the managed package runtime, DataPack export bundles the FlexCard definition with all its dependencies including child cards, data source configurations, and custom CSS. The recommended best practice when deploying is to export dependencies first (Data Mappers, then Integration Procedures) before exporting the FlexCards that reference them."],connections:[{planet:"experience",desc:"Composed FlexCards are placed on Experience Cloud pages"}]}
  ],
  dataFlow:["Data source fetches records from Integration Procedures, SOQL, or APIs","Card state conditions evaluate against the returned data","Active state renders the appropriate layout with bound fields","User interacts with action buttons or flyout triggers","Actions launch OmniScripts, navigate, or invoke backend operations"],
  connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"FlexCards are embedded in OmniScripts as display elements"},{planet:"integration",desc:"FlexCards use Integration Procedures as data sources"},{planet:"datamappers",desc:"FlexCards read data through Data Mapper queries"},{planet:"testing",desc:"FlexCards are tested with preview and UTAM framework"},{planet:"agentforce",desc:"FlexCards serve as context surfaces for agent actions"},{planet:"experience",desc:"FlexCards are placed on Experience Cloud pages"},{planet:"deployment",desc:"FlexCards are exported via DataPacks"},{planet:"lwc",desc:"FlexCards host custom LWC components"}]
},

integration: {
  packages: ['omnistudio'],
  name: "Integration Procedures",
  icon: "\u{1F5A7}",
  color: "#38bdf8",
  description: "The server-side orchestration engine that assembles data, executes business logic, and coordinates callouts without writing Apex code. Integration Procedures (IPs) define declarative action flows that run on the server with full transaction control. The visual designer lets you chain Data Mapper operations, HTTP callouts, Apex invocations, conditional branching, loops, and error handling into complex integration flows. IPs support caching for performance-critical paths, compilation for optimized execution, and can invoke Decision Matrices and Expression Sets for rules-based logic. They serve as the primary backend for OmniScripts and FlexCards.",
  components: [
    {id:"ip-designer",name:"IP Designer",icon:"\u{1F3A8}",desc:"The visual canvas for building server-side action flows. The standard designer creates Integration Procedures up to 2.5 times faster, with access to settings in a single click, connectors for inserting elements between blocks, and drag speed up to 7 times faster than the managed package designer. Debug mode lets you execute the procedure step by step with full JSON inspection at each stage, tracing how data transforms through the flow.",tags:["OmniProcess","OmniProcessElement"],docs:["Integration Procedures are identified by a unique combination of Type and SubType, joined by an underscore (for example, Auto_CreateUpdateQuote). The Type and SubType can contain letters, numbers, and special characters but no spaces. Each IP shares the OmniProcess object with OmniScripts, differentiated by the IsIntegrationProcedure flag. Unlike OmniScripts, Integration Procedures have no end-user interface, run entirely on the server, and can execute synchronously or asynchronously.","The standard designer features an intuitive layout consistent with Salesforce design principles, with connectors between actions that let you easily insert, rearrange, or group elements. You must save after each edit (a deliberate design choice for reliability). The designer requires saving the Integration Procedure before configuring individual actions, which contrasts with the managed package designer where you could configure as you go. Debug mode executes the procedure with full JSON inspection at each step, and the Preview tab shows execution timing.","Integration Procedures have capabilities that OmniScripts lack: caching of part or all of the procedure for performance, unit testing through test procedures, chainable and queueable chainable settings for avoiding governor limits, complex list processing and merging, and invocation from Apex, REST, Flow, and Scheduled Jobs. The standard designer can access settings in a single click, configure procedures in fewer steps, and insert or rearrange elements between blocks using connectors.","Integration Procedures can be invoked from multiple entry points. OmniScripts and FlexCards call them as data sources or action elements. Apex classes use the ConnectApi.OmniDesignerConnect.integrationProcedureExecute method (starting Summer 2025, replacing the managed package method with up to 21% better performance). REST APIs use GET or POST calls. Salesforce Flows call them through custom Apex classes with the InvocableMethod annotation. Batch jobs run them on a schedule for recurring operations."],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"OmniScripts invoke Integration Procedures for backend processing"},{planet:"flexcards",desc:"FlexCards use Integration Procedures as data sources"},{planet:"config",desc:"IP execution respects interaction configuration settings"}]},
    {id:"ip-data-actions",name:"Data Actions",icon:"\u{1F4C0}",desc:"Data Mapper-based actions for reading, writing, and transforming Salesforce data within an Integration Procedure. Extract actions query records with dynamic input parameters for filtering. Post actions write data and return created record IDs for use in subsequent steps. Transform actions reshape JSON structures without database access. Turbo Extract actions use an optimized read path for high-volume queries. Data actions form the backbone of most Integration Procedures.",tags:["OmniProcess","OmniDataTransformation"],docs:["Data Mapper Extract actions invoke a named Data Mapper Extract to query Salesforce data. You configure input parameters as Data Source (the JSON node containing the filter value) and Filter Value (the value to match). The extracted data is accessible to subsequent actions using the Extract action's name as a prefix in merge fields. When used within a Loop Block, each iteration can pass different filter values from the current list item.","Data Mapper Post actions call a named Data Mapper Load to write data back to Salesforce. Additional Input parameters pass values from the procedure's data JSON using merge field syntax. The output includes created record IDs organized by type and order. When used in a Loop Block, be aware that each iteration counts against the 150 DML statement governor limit.","Data Mapper Transform actions reshape JSON data between steps without database access. They are commonly used to normalize data from different sources or to map data to external system formats like DocuSign templates. The Ignore Cache option disables any caching configured on the underlying Data Mapper.","All data actions support Send and Response transformation properties. The Send JSON Path specifies which node of the data JSON to pass as input, and the Response JSON Node determines where returned data is placed. Additional Output key-value pairs can merge other data into the procedure's JSON. These properties enable precise control over data flow between actions."],connections:[{planet:"datamappers",desc:"Data actions invoke Data Mapper definitions for CRUD operations"}]},
    {id:"ip-http-remote",name:"HTTP & Remote Actions",icon:"\u{1F310}",desc:"Actions for communicating with external systems and custom Apex code. HTTP Actions make REST or SOAP callouts to third-party APIs with configurable headers and authentication. Remote Actions invoke Apex classes implementing the Callable interface or invoke Salesforce Invocable Actions using DefaultInvocableAction as the class. Email Actions send templated notifications. These actions extend Integration Procedures beyond Salesforce data into external integrations.",tags:["OmniProcess"],docs:["Remote Actions invoke Apex classes that implement the Callable interface (or the legacy VlocityOpenInterface). You specify the Remote Class name (with namespace prefix in standard runtime, for example omnistudio.ClassName), the Remote Method, and any Additional Input parameters. The reserialize option forces the output back into standard format when the Apex class returns non-standard data structures. The useStandardRuntime option forces standard runtime execution even when Managed Package Runtime is enabled.","Remote Actions can also invoke Salesforce Invocable Actions by specifying DefaultInvocableAction as the Remote Class and the invocable action name as the Remote Method. The InvocableInputKey option specifies a JSON map as input. This enables Integration Procedures to call Flows, quick actions, and other invocable services declaratively.","HTTP Actions make REST callouts with configurable URLs, headers, request bodies, and authentication. They support both GET and POST methods and can map response fields to the procedure's data JSON. For external systems requiring OAuth or Named Credentials, authentication is configured at the Salesforce platform level and referenced in the action.","Email Actions send templated email notifications through Salesforce email services, useful for sending confirmations, notifications, or status updates as part of an automated process. All three action types support the Execution Conditional Formula property, which controls whether the action executes based on data conditions, and the Send/Response Transformation properties for JSON manipulation."],connections:[]},
    {id:"ip-flow-control",name:"Flow Control Blocks",icon:"\u{1F500}",desc:"Structural elements that control execution flow within an Integration Procedure. Conditional Blocks execute actions when expressions evaluate to true or manage mutually exclusive conditions. Loop Blocks iterate over list data, processing one item at a time. Try-Catch Blocks provide error handling with fallback logic. Cache Blocks store results with configurable TTL values using Session or Org cache types. Blocks can be nested within other blocks.",tags:["OmniProcessElement"],docs:["Loop Blocks iterate over a JSON array, processing one item at a time. You specify the array in the Loop List parameter (for example, Products:Ids), and each iteration receives a single element from the array. Actions within the Loop Block can reference the current item's fields through the standard merge field syntax. Be aware that lists with more than 1000 items degrade performance for Data Mapper Transform calls within loops. A paging strategy can break up long lists to maintain performance.","Cache Blocks store the results of their child actions for configurable durations, reducing database queries and API callouts for frequently accessed data. The Salesforce Platform Cache Type setting controls cache scope: Session Cache for user-specific data (maximum 8 hours) or Org Cache for shared data (maximum 48 hours, default 24 hours). The minimum TTL is 5 minutes. Field-level security checks can be configured for cached data, though enabling FLS disables Org Cache.","Conditional Blocks (If-Else) control the Integration Procedure flow by executing their child actions only when an Execution Conditional Formula evaluates to true. They can also contain steps with mutually exclusive conditions, creating branch paths through the procedure. Try-Catch Blocks wrap actions so that if any action fails, the error is caught and the procedure continues running with the fallback logic defined in the catch section.","All blocks share the Execution Conditional Formula property, which determines whether the block executes at all. If the formula evaluates to false or is undefined, the block is skipped entirely. Blocks can be nested within each other, for example a Loop Block inside a Try-Catch Block to handle errors during iteration, or a Cache Block containing multiple data retrieval actions that should all expire together."],connections:[]},
    {id:"ip-decision-actions",name:"Decision & Intelligence Actions",icon:"\u{1F9E0}",desc:"Actions that invoke rules-based decision logic within Integration Procedures. Decision Matrix actions look up values from configurable matrix tables based on input criteria, supporting complex pricing, eligibility, and routing decisions. Expression Set actions evaluate multi-step business rules with variable assignments and conditional logic. Assert actions validate data conditions and halt execution with descriptive errors when assertions fail, enabling unit testing of Integration Procedures.",tags:["OmniProcess"],docs:["Decision Matrix actions look up values from configurable matrix tables stored in the Business Rules Engine. Given a set of input criteria, the matrix returns matching output values. This is ideal for complex pricing lookups, eligibility determinations, underwriting decisions, and routing rules where the decision logic is data-driven and frequently updated by business analysts without developer involvement.","Expression Set actions evaluate multi-step business rules defined in the Business Rules Engine. Expression Sets support variable assignments, conditional branches, and multi-step calculations that go beyond simple formula expressions. They are used for complex rule evaluation scenarios like insurance rate calculations, compliance checks, and multi-factor eligibility assessments.","Assert actions declare expected results for unit testing Integration Procedures. When the assert condition fails, execution halts with a descriptive error message. Test Procedures are special Integration Procedures designed specifically for unit testing, where Assert actions validate that data operations and transformations produce expected outputs. In the standard runtime, HTTP mocking is not available for test execution, so real HTTP calls occur during tests.","The Execution Conditional Formula property on these actions controls whether they execute based on data conditions. This allows you to conditionally invoke decision logic only when certain criteria are met, for example only running a pricing matrix lookup when a product category has been selected. All three action types integrate with the broader Business Rules Engine product for organizations that need sophisticated rules management."],connections:[{planet:"formulas",desc:"Decision actions use expression evaluation for complex rule logic"}]},
    {id:"ip-utility-actions",name:"Utility Actions",icon:"\u{1F6E0}",desc:"General-purpose actions for common operations within Integration Procedures. List actions merge multiple lists by matching key values, with an Advanced Merge option for nodes with different names or nesting levels. Set Values actions assign static values, merge fields, concatenations, or formula results to JSON nodes. Response actions end the procedure and shape the output JSON. Batch actions run Scheduled Jobs, and Chatter actions post to feeds.",tags:["OmniProcess"],docs:["Set Values actions are one of the most frequently used utility actions. They assign values to JSON nodes using literal values, merge fields from previous steps (percent-sign syntax), concatenated strings, formula expressions, or combinations of all four. Common patterns include renaming nodes to simplify paths, performing calculations like tax computations, creating JSON structures for output, and defining arrays. Any text between percent signs is treated as a merge field, so literal percent signs require the $Vlocity.Percent environment variable.","List actions merge two or more lists by matching values of specified JSON nodes. A basic merge matches node names exactly across the input lists. The Advanced Merge option handles lists where the matching nodes have different names or reside at different nesting levels, using Matching Path and Matching Group settings. List inputs must be in array format even if they contain only one item; single-object results from Data Mapper Extracts may need a Transform step first.","Response actions end an Integration Procedure and return data to the caller. They can return the full data JSON, only specified Additional Output key-value pairs, or a combination. The Return Only Additional Output option discards all data except the explicitly specified outputs, while Return Full Data JSON sends everything. Response Headers can add custom values to the HTTP response header, including overriding the status code. The Execution Conditional Formula property allows conditional termination based on data conditions.","Batch actions run Salesforce Scheduled Jobs for recurring operations like billing cycles or policy renewal scans. Chatter actions create posts to feeds and groups, enabling social collaboration from automated processes. Delete actions remove records from Salesforce objects. These utility actions round out the Integration Procedure toolkit, handling operational tasks that complement the core data retrieval and transformation capabilities."],connections:[]},
    {id:"ip-compilation",name:"IP Activation & Caching",icon:"\u{1F680}",desc:"Compilation and performance optimization for Integration Procedures. Activation compiles the procedure definition into an optimized execution plan with instant activation in the standard designer. Cache Blocks support Session Cache (user-specific, max 8 hours) and Org Cache (shared, max 48 hours) with minimum 5-minute TTL. Long-running Integration Procedures support chainable and queueable settings to avoid governor limits on complex operations.",tags:["OmniProcessCompilation","OmniProcess"],docs:["Activation compiles all action configurations, merge fields, and data mappings into a single optimized payload stored in an Omni Process Compilation record. This compiled form is loaded at runtime to avoid re-processing the action tree on every execution. The standard designer provides instant activation, eliminating the compilation delay experienced with the managed package designer.","Caching can be applied at the top level of the entire procedure or selectively through Cache Blocks on specific action groups. Top-level caching uses the ResponseCacheType field with Session or Org scope. Cache Blocks within the procedure enable different TTL values for different data sections, so frequently changing data can have shorter expiration while reference data uses longer caching. The Ignore Cache option on individual data actions overrides the cache for specific calls during development.","Long-running Integration Procedures support chainable and queueable chainable execution modes to avoid governor limits on complex operations. Chainable mode breaks the procedure into separate transactions, while queueable chainable mode uses the Salesforce queueable framework for asynchronous processing. These settings are configured in the procedure's properties and are essential for procedures that process large datasets or make many callouts.","Version management tracks all iterations of an Integration Procedure with numbered versions. Only one version can be active at a time for a given Type and SubType combination. The standard runtime supports deployment between orgs using Salesforce CLI (recommended) or DataPacks for managed package environments. When exporting with Salesforce CLI, associated Data Mappers should be exported first, followed by Integration Procedures, then OmniScripts and FlexCards that reference them."],connections:[{planet:"deployment",desc:"Compiled Integration Procedures are packaged in DataPacks"}]}
  ],
  dataFlow:["OmniScript or FlexCard invokes the Integration Procedure","Data actions extract records from Salesforce via Data Mappers","Flow control blocks apply conditional logic, loops, and error handling","HTTP and Remote actions call external APIs and Apex classes","Response action shapes the output JSON returned to the caller"],
  connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"Integration Procedures provide backend logic for OmniScripts"},{planet:"flexcards",desc:"Integration Procedures serve as data sources for FlexCards"},{planet:"datamappers",desc:"Integration Procedures invoke Data Mapper operations"},{planet:"formulas",desc:"Integration Procedures use formula expressions in decision logic"},{planet:"config",desc:"Integration Procedures respect interaction configuration"},{planet:"deployment",desc:"Integration Procedures are exported via DataPacks"}]
},

datamappers: {
  packages: ['omnistudio'],
  name: "Data Mappers",
  icon: "\u{1F504}",
  color: "#fb923c",
  description: "The declarative data access layer that handles all reading, writing, and transformation of Salesforce data within OmniStudio. Data Mappers provide a visual interface for building SOQL queries, mapping JSON fields to SObject fields for DML operations, and reshaping data structures without touching the database. Four types serve distinct purposes: Extract reads data, Load writes data, Transform reshapes JSON, and Turbo Extract handles high-performance bulk reads. Data Mappers are the primary mechanism through which OmniScripts and Integration Procedures interact with Salesforce data, replacing the need for custom Apex data access classes.",
  components: [
    {id:"dm-extract",name:"Extract (Read)",icon:"\u{1F4E5}",desc:"A declarative SOQL query builder that reads data from Salesforce objects and returns it as structured JSON. The visual interface lets you select objects, fields, and filter criteria without writing SOQL. Extract supports parent-child relationship queries, cross-object field references, and dynamic filter values passed from calling OmniScripts or Integration Procedures. Field-level output mapping transforms the raw query results into the JSON structure your components expect.",tags:["OmniDataTransformation","OmniDataTransformationItem"],docs:["Extract Data Mappers build SOQL queries visually by selecting objects, fields, and filter criteria. The input side defines what data to read, including the source object and filter conditions that can reference dynamic values passed from calling components. The output side maps query result fields to the JSON structure your OmniScripts and FlexCards expect, including renaming fields, flattening relationships, and applying formulas during extraction.","Data Mapper metadata is automatically cached. If you use the Scale Cache, this automatic caching occurs unless you turn it off. If you use the Platform Cache, you must allocate space in the VlocityMetadata cache partition. Data caching can be separately configured on the Options tab with Session Cache (max 8 hours) or Org Cache (max 48 hours) and a configurable Time To Live. Field-level security enforcement can be enabled to check user permissions before executing, though this disables Org Cache.","Data Mappers can be invoked from OmniScripts using Data Mapper Extract Action or Turbo Action elements, from Integration Procedures using Extract or Turbo Extract actions, from Apex classes using the ConnectApi.OmniDesignerConnect.executeDataMapper method, from REST APIs using GET requests, and from Salesforce Flows through Integration Procedures. The REST API supports both ID-based retrieval and parameter-based queries.","Each Data Mapper is identified by a unique Interface Name (containing letters, numbers, and dashes but no spaces). When an Extract returns a list with only one item, it may convert the result to a single object instead of a list. If downstream processing expects a list, use a Transform Data Mapper to convert the single object back to list format."],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"OmniScripts invoke Extract Data Mappers to populate form data"},{planet:"integration",desc:"Integration Procedures use Extract actions for data retrieval"}]},
    {id:"dm-load",name:"Load (Write)",icon:"\u{1F4E4}",desc:"Maps JSON data from OmniScript or Integration Procedure output to Salesforce object fields for DML operations. The visual mapper lets you bind JSON paths to SObject fields, handling both insert and upsert operations. Load supports multi-object writes in a single operation, with configurable field mappings for parent and child records. The bulkUpload parameter switches to batch Apex for large datasets, and the SynchronousProcessThreshold field controls when processing shifts to asynchronous mode.",tags:["OmniDataTransformation","OmniDataTransformationItem"],docs:["Load Data Mappers write data to Salesforce by mapping JSON input fields to object fields. The visual mapper interface shows input JSON on the left and target Salesforce objects and fields on the right. Mappings define which JSON paths write to which fields, with the DomainObjectFieldType ensuring proper type casting during DML operations. Both insert and upsert operations are supported, and multi-object writes can create or update records across parent and child objects in a single operation.","Load Data Mappers return detailed results including created object IDs organized by type (createdObjectsByType) and by processing order (createdObjectsByOrder), along with any errors that occurred during DML. Error details include per-field errors (errorsByField) and the input JSON annotated with per-node errors (errorsAsJson). This granular error reporting allows calling components to display user-friendly messages about specific validation failures.","The REST API supports invoking Load Data Mappers with a POST request that includes the bundle name, object list (the JSON data to load), an optional files list for base64-encoded file attachments, and a bulkUpload flag that switches to batch Apex for large datasets. The Apex ConnectApi method provides up to 60% better performance compared to the legacy managed package method for programmatic invocations.","Load Data Mappers can also write to Salesforce Platform Events by mapping JSON fields to platform event fields. This enables OmniScripts and Integration Procedures to fire events as part of their process flow. The Transform variant with a DocuSign output type specifically maps OmniScript data to DocuSign template fields for e-signature workflows."],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"OmniScripts invoke Load Data Mappers to save collected data"},{planet:"integration",desc:"Integration Procedures use Post actions to write data via Data Mappers"}]},
    {id:"dm-transform",name:"Transform (JSON-to-JSON)",icon:"\u{1F503}",desc:"Reshapes JSON data structures without any database access, making it a pure data transformation tool. Transform Data Mappers map fields between different JSON schemas, flatten nested structures, aggregate values, and restructure data. They also support DocuSign output type for mapping OmniScript data to e-signature template fields. Commonly used between Integration Procedure steps to normalize data from different sources before presenting it to OmniScripts or FlexCards.",tags:["OmniDataTransformation","OmniDataTransformationItem"],docs:["Transform Data Mappers operate entirely on JSON data without any database access, making them pure data transformation tools with no DML or SOQL overhead. The input side accepts JSON from OmniScripts, Integration Procedures, or other Data Mappers. The output side defines the target JSON structure with field mappings that can rename, restructure, flatten, or aggregate the input data. Formula expressions can be applied during mapping to compute derived values.","The DocuSign output type is a specialized Transform variant that maps OmniScript or Integration Procedure data to DocuSign template custom fields. When you set the Output Type to DocuSign and specify a Target Output DocuSign Template ID, the mapper fetches the template's field definitions and lets you map input JSON paths to DocuSign text tabs, checkbox tabs, and radio button tabs. The Quick Match feature automatically pairs fields with matching names.","Transform Data Mappers can convert single objects to lists and vice versa, which is important when working with Data Mapper Extracts that return a single record as an object rather than a list. If downstream processing expects a list format, a Transform step can wrap the object in an array. This is a common pattern when preparing data for List actions in Integration Procedures that require array inputs.","The Overwrite target for all null inputs option on the configuration controls whether null values from the input JSON are written to the output or ignored. The standard designer creates Data Mappers up to six times faster than the managed package designer, with simplified mapping functionality and easy visualization of connections between input and output objects."],connections:[{planet:"integration",desc:"Integration Procedures use Transform actions between processing steps"}]},
    {id:"dm-turbo",name:"Turbo Extract",icon:"\u{26A1}",desc:"A high-performance variant of Extract optimized for bulk data reads. Turbo Extract uses a streamlined execution path that bypasses some of the overhead of standard Extract, delivering significantly faster query execution for large result sets. It supports the same visual query builder interface with the same input parameter, filter, and output mapping capabilities. Best suited for Integration Procedures and OmniScripts that need to process thousands of records efficiently.",tags:["OmniDataTransformation","OmniDataTransformationItem"],docs:["Turbo Extract Data Mappers function identically to standard Extract Data Mappers in terms of configuration, using the same visual query builder for selecting objects, fields, and filter criteria. The difference is in the execution engine: Turbo Extract uses an optimized read path that reduces processing overhead for large result sets. This makes it the preferred choice for data retrieval operations that return hundreds or thousands of records.","In Integration Procedures, the Data Mapper Turbo Action works exactly like the Data Mapper Extract Action in configuration. The only difference is that the Data Mapper Interface property lists Turbo Extract Data Mappers instead of standard Extracts. Input parameters, filter values, and caching options work identically between the two action types.","In OmniScripts, a Turbo Action element invokes a Turbo Extract to load data. This is commonly used to populate Select, Multi-Select, and Radio elements with option lists, or to prefill form fields with existing record data. The Turbo Action element configuration mirrors the standard Data Mapper Extract Action element.","Caching applies to Turbo Extract the same way as standard Extract. Metadata caching is automatic, and data caching can be configured on the Options tab with Session or Org cache types. The standard designer provides the same streamlined creation experience for Turbo Extracts as for other Data Mapper types."],connections:[{planet:"integration",desc:"Integration Procedures use Turbo Extract for high-volume data reads"}]},
    {id:"dm-formulas",name:"Mapping Formulas",icon:"\u{1F9EE}",desc:"Field-level formula expressions within Data Mapper mappings that compute derived values during extract and transform operations. Formulas can concatenate strings, perform arithmetic on numeric fields, format dates, apply conditional logic with IF/CASE statements, and reference multiple source fields in a single output mapping. These inline formulas reduce the need for separate transformation steps by handling field-level computation directly within the Data Mapper definition.",docUrl:"https://help.salesforce.com/s/articleView?id=sf.os_function_reference_56716.htm&type=5",tags:["OmniDataTransformationItem"],connections:[{planet:"formulas",desc:"Mapping formulas use the same function library as OmniStudio formulas"}]}
  ],
  dataFlow:["Extract Data Mapper queries Salesforce objects and returns JSON","Transform Data Mapper reshapes the data structure for component consumption","OmniScript or FlexCard displays the mapped data to the user","User input is collected and mapped to SObject fields","Load Data Mapper writes the data back to Salesforce records"],
  connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"Data Mappers provide data read/write for OmniScripts"},{planet:"flexcards",desc:"Data Mappers supply query data for FlexCard data sources"},{planet:"integration",desc:"Data Mappers are invoked as actions within Integration Procedures"},{planet:"formulas",desc:"Data Mapper mappings use formula expressions"},{planet:"deployment",desc:"Data Mappers are exported via DataPacks"}]
},

formulas: {
  packages: ['omnistudio'],
  name: "Functions & Formulas",
  icon: "\u{1D453}",
  color: "#facc15",
  description: "A comprehensive expression language that powers calculations, data transformations, and conditional logic across all OmniStudio components. The formula engine provides over 100 functions spanning math, string manipulation, date operations, list processing, and JSON navigation. Formulas appear in OmniScript SetValues and Formula elements, Data Mapper mapping expressions, and Integration Procedure conditional evaluations. The function library supports eleven data types with automatic coercion and explicit conversion functions, enabling complex business calculations without custom code.",
  components: [
    {id:"fn-math-logic",name:"Math & Logical Functions",icon:"\u{2795}",desc:"Arithmetic and decision-making functions for business calculations. In OmniScripts, supported operators include addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, power, equals, not-equals, comparisons, AND, OR, and parentheses. Functions include ABS, ROUND, POW, INTEGER, NUMBER, RANDOM, CURRENCY, BOOLEAN, and NULL. Logical functions IF, CASE (with UPPER, LOWER, SENTENCE, TITLE), AND, OR, EQUALS, COUNTIF, and SUMIF power conditional evaluation and list processing.",docUrl:"https://help.salesforce.com/s/articleView?id=xcloud.os_omniscript_functions.htm&type=5",tags:["OmniProcessElement"],docs:["OmniScript Formula and Aggregate elements use a rich expression language with standard arithmetic operators (+, -, *, /, ^), comparison operators (=, <>, >, <, >=, <=), and logical operators (&&, ||). Formulas support merge fields referencing other elements (wrapped in percent signs), numbers, string literals in quotes, booleans, arrays, dates, and null values. The Formula element handles single-value calculations, while the Aggregate element is designed for operations on repeatable data from Edit Blocks.","The IF function evaluates a condition and returns one of two values: IF(expression, then_value, else_value). The EQUALS function compares a field to a specific value and is useful when the value contains special characters. CASE changes text case with four modes: UPPER, LOWER, SENTENCE, and TITLE. COUNTIF and SUMIF operate on arrays, returning counts or sums of elements that meet a condition.","In Data Mappers and Integration Procedures, the function library is broader and includes over 100 functions with separate operator and function sets. Operators include standard arithmetic, comparison, and logical operators plus string operations. Functions span categories including math, string manipulation, date operations, list processing, conditional logic, and type conversion. The VALUELOOKUP function dynamically maps values from one list to another.","The ROUND function accepts a number and decimal places count. Note that when using SUM inside a Formula element, the expression defaults to two decimal places regardless of the specified precision. For exact decimal control, use ROUND with the plus operator instead of SUM. The RANDOM function returns a value between zero and one and is commonly used for A/B testing scenarios."],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"Math and logical functions power OmniScript calculations"},{planet:"integration",desc:"Logical functions drive conditional branching in Integration Procedures"}]},
    {id:"fn-string",name:"String Functions",icon:"\u{1F524}",desc:"Text manipulation functions for formatting, parsing, and validating string data. In OmniScripts, CONCATENATE joins elements into a single string, CONTAINS checks for substring presence, SPLIT divides text by a delimiter with an optional limit, STRING converts any value to text, and SUBSTRING extracts characters between two indexes. In Data Mappers and Integration Procedures, the full function library includes LEFT, RIGHT, MID, LEN, TRIM, SUBSTITUTE, REPLACE, and REGEX.",tags:["OmniProcessElement"],docs:["OmniScript string functions work within Formula and Aggregate elements. CONCATENATE accepts multiple values and joins them into a single string, for example CONCATENATE(FirstName, \" \", LastName). CONTAINS evaluates whether a value exists within a string and returns true or false. SPLIT divides text by a delimiter token with an optional limit parameter. STRING converts any data type to a text representation.","The CASE function with string modes changes text case: UPPER converts all characters to uppercase, LOWER to lowercase, SENTENCE capitalizes only the first character, and TITLE capitalizes the first character of each word. SUBSTRING extracts characters between start and end index positions. These functions are commonly used for display formatting, generating reference codes, and normalizing user input.","In Data Mappers and Integration Procedures, the string function library is substantially larger. It includes LEFT, RIGHT, and MID for positional extraction, LEN for string length, TRIM for whitespace removal, UPPER and LOWER for case conversion, SUBSTITUTE and REPLACE for text replacement, and REGEX for pattern matching. These functions work within formula expressions in mapping configurations and Set Values actions.","String operations in Integration Procedure Set Values actions support concatenation of merge fields with literal text using the format \"Text: %mergeField%\". The plus operator with an equals prefix (=) enables formula-style string concatenation, for example =%Inputs:FirstName% + \" \" + %Inputs:LastName%. Any text between percent signs is interpreted as a merge field reference."],connections:[]},
    {id:"fn-date-time",name:"Date & Time Functions",icon:"\u{1F4C5}",desc:"Functions for working with dates, times, and durations in business process calculations. TODAY returns the current date (time set to midnight) and NOW returns the current date and time in UTC. AGE and AGEON calculate age in years from a birth date. DATEDIFF returns the difference between two dates in days. DATE, YEAR, MONTH, DAYOFMONTH, DAYOFWEEK, HOUR, and MINUTE extract components. The MOMENT function provides access to the Moment.js library for complex date manipulation.",tags:["OmniProcessElement"],docs:["In OmniScripts, date functions work with Date elements and produce JavaScript date objects. TODAY returns the current date with time set to midnight. NOW returns the current date and time with milliseconds always set to zero. The $Vlocity.NOW environment variable applies the user or org time zone, while the NOW function applies UTC time. DATEDIFF calculates the absolute difference between two dates in days, always returning a positive integer.","AGE calculates a person's current age in years from a date of birth, while AGEON calculates age as of a specific future date. DATE converts a value to a JavaScript date object. YEAR, MONTH, DAYOFMONTH, and DAYOFWEEK extract individual date components (DAYOFWEEK returns 1 for Monday through 7 for Sunday). HOUR and MINUTE extract time components according to local time.","The MOMENT function provides access to the Moment.js library for complex date formatting, calculations, manipulation, and comparisons. It must contain parameters (for example MOMENT(NOW())) and supports chaining methods like .add(1, 'year').subtract(1, 'day'). Appending .calendar() is a recommended best practice. This enables sophisticated date logic like calculating policy expiration dates or contract renewal windows.","In Data Mappers and Integration Procedures, the date function library includes ADDDAY, ADDMONTH, ADDYEAR for date arithmetic, EOM (end of month), TODATE and TODATETIME for parsing, and DATEFORMAT for display formatting. Complex date calculations can be nested, for example ADDDAY(EOM(ADDMONTH(TODAY(),-1)),1) returns the first day of the current month. Formulas with a Date data type are interpreted according to the Date Format setting using the Day.js library."],connections:[]},
    {id:"fn-list-json",name:"List & JSON Functions",icon:"\u{1F4CB}",desc:"Functions for navigating and manipulating structured data within OmniStudio's JSON data model. In OmniScripts, ARRAY creates arrays from element values, SUM/AVERAGE/COUNT/MIN/MAX/EXISTS operate on repeatable elements from Edit Blocks. Array values are accessed using listnode|listnumber notation. In Data Mappers and Integration Procedures, LIST, VLOOKUP, FLATTEN, LISTMERGE, LISTMERGEPRIMARY, LISTSIZE, SORTBY, FILTER, AVG, and IF functions provide comprehensive list processing.",tags:["OmniProcessElement","OmniDataTransformationItem"],docs:["In OmniScripts, the ARRAY function creates an array from individual element values, for example ARRAY(Child1, Child2, Child3, Child4). Aggregate functions SUM, AVERAGE, COUNT, MIN, and MAX operate on repeatable elements from Edit Blocks, returning totals, averages, counts, and extremes across all rows. EXISTS checks whether a value appears in one or more elements, returning true or false.","The pipe-number notation (listnode|listnumber) accesses specific items in an array by index. For example, DeptArray:Departments|2 retrieves the second item from the Departments array. This notation works in Set Values elements and Formula expressions, enabling direct access to array positions without loops. When combined with IF functions, this creates lookup-style logic based on data conditions.","In Data Mappers and Integration Procedures, the function library includes specialized list functions. LIST creates arrays, VLOOKUP searches lists by key values, FLATTEN converts nested arrays to flat lists, and SORTBY orders list items by a specified field. LISTMERGE and LISTMERGEPRIMARY combine lists with different merge strategies. LISTSIZE returns the count of items in a list. FILTER selects list items matching criteria.","Integration Procedure List actions provide additional list processing capabilities beyond formula functions. Basic merge matches nodes by exact name across lists. Advanced Merge handles lists with different node names or nesting levels, using Matching Path and Matching Group settings to align records. Input lists must be in array format, and single-object Data Mapper results may need a Transform step to convert to list format before processing."],connections:[{planet:"datamappers",desc:"JSON functions process list data in Data Mapper transformations"}]},
    {id:"fn-datatypes",name:"Data Types & Conversion",icon:"\u{1F522}",desc:"Eleven data types with explicit conversion functions for ensuring type correctness across component boundaries. Supported types include Text, Number, Currency, Date, DateTime, Time, Boolean, Percent, Phone, Email, and URL. In OmniScripts, BOOLEAN, CURRENCY, INTEGER, NUMBER, and STRING convert between types. In Data Mappers and Integration Procedures, TOTEXT, TONUMBER, TODATE, TODATETIME, and TOBOOLEAN provide comprehensive type conversion.",tags:["OmniProcessElement"],docs:["OmniScript conversion functions operate within Formula and Aggregate elements. BOOLEAN converts a value to true or false. CURRENCY formats a number for currency display (12345 becomes 12,345.00), with a Mask property controlling decimal precision. INTEGER converts to a whole number without rounding (12.5 becomes 12). NUMBER converts a string to a numeric value. STRING converts any value to text. The NULL constant explicitly sets a value to null.","Data Mapper and Integration Procedure data types include Text, Long Text, Number, Integer, Currency, Date, DateTime, Time, Boolean, Percent, and JSON. The type system is important for Data Mapper field mappings, where the DomainObjectFieldType on each mapping item ensures proper type casting during Load operations. Mismatched types between the JSON data and the target Salesforce field can cause silent data loss or DML errors.","Type coercion in OmniScript formulas follows standard rules: numbers and strings can be compared, dates are compared chronologically, and boolean values are interpreted as true/false. When operators like the equals sign (=) are used in Set Values expressions, adding spaces before and after distinguishes it from the assignment equals sign. The equals prefix (=) at the start of a value tells the engine to evaluate the rest as a formula expression rather than a literal value.","In Integration Procedure Set Values actions, the TOSTRING function prevents large numbers from being converted to scientific notation. This is important when working with identifiers that look like numbers but should be treated as text. Wrapping an IF function in TOSTRING ensures the output is always a string, for example =TOSTRING(IF(condition, value1, value2)). The $Vlocity.Percent environment variable represents literal percent signs in formulas where percent signs normally denote merge fields."],connections:[]}
  ],
  dataFlow:["Formula element or SetValues references a function expression","Expression parser tokenizes the formula string","Functions evaluate against the current JSON data context","Type coercion converts operands as needed","Computed result updates the OmniScript data model or Data Mapper mapping"],
  connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"Formulas power calculations in OmniScript elements"},{planet:"integration",desc:"Formulas drive conditional logic in Integration Procedures"},{planet:"datamappers",desc:"Formulas compute derived values in Data Mapper mappings"}]
},

lwc: {
  packages: ['omnistudio'],
  name: "Custom LWC Extensions",
  icon: "\u{1F4BB}",
  color: "#60a5fa",
  description: "The developer extension point for OmniStudio, enabling custom Lightning Web Components to participate in OmniScript and FlexCard compositions. When the declarative palette doesn't cover a requirement, developers build custom LWC elements that appear alongside standard elements in the designer. Custom elements inherit the OmniScript data context, can read and write to the JSON data model through a documented API, and fire events that integrate with OmniScript navigation and validation. For FlexCards, custom LWC components extend the rendering capabilities beyond the built-in element types.",
  components: [
    {id:"lwc-custom-elements",name:"Custom OmniScript Elements",icon:"\u{1F9E9}",desc:"Developer-built Lightning Web Components that integrate into the OmniScript designer palette as first-class elements. Custom elements extend the OmniElement base class, inheriting data binding, validation, and navigation capabilities. The recommended limit is 30 custom LWCs per OmniScript. Common use cases include custom file viewers, specialized input controls, map integrations, and rich media displays that the declarative palette cannot produce.",tags:["OmniProcessElement"],docs:["Custom LWC elements extend the Omniscript Base Mixin component or an individual Omniscript element's Lightning Web Component. Components extending the Base Mixin have full access to the OmniScript header definition through this.omniScriptHeaderDef, while components extending specific elements use this.scriptHeaderDef. Both approaches provide access to the data JSON, custom labels, and the element's configured properties.","The Custom LWC element in the OmniScript designer supports two modes: interactive elements that communicate with the OmniScript's data model, and standalone components that render independently without data model interaction. Interactive elements use the data binding API to read and write values, participate in validation, and respond to navigation events. Standalone components are useful for displaying external content or custom visualizations that do not affect the OmniScript data.","Custom LWCs must be deployed to the Salesforce org before they can be referenced in OmniScripts. For multi-language OmniScripts, custom components access custom labels through the allCustomLabels attribute on the script header definition. Additional custom labels not automatically available can be specified using the moreCustomLabels property in the OmniScript's JSON configuration."],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"Custom elements appear in the OmniScript designer palette"}]},
    {id:"lwc-custom-cards",name:"Custom FlexCard Components",icon:"\u{1F5BC}",desc:"Lightning Web Components that extend FlexCard rendering beyond the built-in element types. Custom card components receive the FlexCard's data context and can render specialized visualizations, interactive charts, or complex layouts that the declarative designer cannot produce. They integrate with FlexCard actions and can trigger flyouts and OmniScript launches through the card's event system.",tags:["OmniUiCard"],docs:["Custom FlexCard components receive the parent card's data context and can render any UI that standard FlexCard elements cannot produce, such as interactive charts, maps, custom data visualizations, or complex table layouts. These components are deployed as standard Lightning Web Components and then referenced from within the FlexCard designer.","When a FlexCard is activated on the managed package runtime, activation generates an LWC bundle that includes the custom component references. On the standard runtime with the standard designer, the standard FlexCard component handles rendering without generating a separate LWC. Custom CSS classes created in the FlexCard designer are saved as Salesforce attachments and included in the compiled component package.","Custom card components can participate in the FlexCard's action and event system, responding to user interactions and triggering flyouts, navigation, or OmniScript launches through published events. For Experience Cloud LWR sites, keeping Managed Package Runtime enabled is required for FlexCards with custom LWC components, as the standard FlexCard component on LWR sites does not support all custom component patterns."],connections:[{planet:"flexcards",desc:"Custom components extend FlexCard rendering capabilities"}]},
    {id:"lwc-data-binding",name:"Data Context & Events",icon:"\u{1F517}",desc:"The JavaScript API that custom LWC elements use to interact with the OmniScript JSON data model. The omniGetMergeField method reads values from the data tree, omniUpdateDataJson writes values back, and omniValidate integrates with step-level validation. Custom events like omniNavigateTo control step navigation, and omniAggregate participates in Aggregate element calculations. This API ensures custom elements behave identically to built-in elements from the OmniScript engine's perspective.",tags:["OmniProcess","OmniProcessElement"],docs:["The OmniScript data binding API provides methods for reading, writing, and validating data within the JSON data model. omniGetMergeField reads values from any path in the data tree, enabling custom elements to access data collected by other elements. omniUpdateDataJson writes values back to the data model, triggering downstream recalculations and conditional evaluations just as standard element changes would.","The omniValidate method integrates custom validation logic with the OmniScript's step-level validation system. When a user attempts to navigate forward, the OmniScript engine calls omniValidate on all custom elements in the current step, and any validation failures prevent navigation. The omniNavigateTo event controls step navigation from custom elements, enabling scenarios like jumping to specific steps based on custom logic.","The omniAggregate method enables custom elements to participate in Aggregate element calculations, contributing their values to SUM, AVERAGE, COUNT, and other aggregate operations alongside standard elements. ReadMe reference documentation for each base OmniScript LWC component is available, providing the specific properties, methods, and events that custom extensions can override or extend."],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"Data context API connects custom elements to OmniScript data model"}]}
  ],
  dataFlow:["Developer creates an LWC extending the OmniElement base class","Component is registered in the OmniScript or FlexCard metadata","Designer palette displays the custom element for drag-and-drop placement","At runtime, the element receives data context and renders custom UI","User interactions update the JSON data model through the binding API"],
  connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"Custom LWCs extend the OmniScript element palette"},{planet:"flexcards",desc:"Custom LWCs extend FlexCard rendering"}]
},

config: {
  packages: ['omnistudio'],
  name: "Configuration & Settings",
  icon: "\u{2699}",
  color: "#64748b",
  description: "Central administration settings that govern how OmniStudio components behave across your org. OmniInteractionConfig records control runtime behavior like session persistence, caching policies, and feature toggles. Global auto number definitions generate sequential identifiers for business processes. Usage-based entitlements track component execution against licensed limits. Electronic signature integration connects OmniScripts to DocuSign templates for legally binding signature capture. These settings provide the operational foundation that all other OmniStudio domains depend on.",
  components: [
    {id:"cfg-interaction",name:"Interaction Configuration",icon:"\u{1F4CB}",desc:"Configuration records for OmniStudio component behavior. The primary runtime toggle is Managed Package Runtime in OmniStudio Settings (Setup), which determines standard vs. managed package objects and APIs. Omni Interaction Configuration records (also in Setup) manage supplementary key-value settings like ApexClassCheck for security enforcement, EnableLightningRTE for rich text editor selection, SkipUserProfileOnOSLoad for preview performance, and RetainDesignerSettingOnUpgrade.",tags:["OmniInteractionConfig"],docs:["The two most important OmniStudio settings live in Setup under OmniStudio Settings: Managed Package Runtime (determines whether components use standard or managed package objects) and Managed Package Designer (determines which designer opens). Disabling Managed Package Runtime enables standard runtime where activation is instant and deployment uses Salesforce CLI. Disabling Managed Package Designer switches to the standard designer with improved performance.","Omni Interaction Configuration records are key-value pairs in Setup that control runtime behavior across all OmniStudio components. Key security settings include ApexClassCheck (requires explicit Apex class access for remote actions), EnforceDMFLSAndDataEncryption (enforces field-level security for all Data Mappers), and EnableQueryWithFLS (enforces field-level security for SOQL and SOSL queries in FlexCards). As of February 2026, Salesforce enables these security settings by default.","Additional configuration records control feature behavior: EnableLightningRTE switches from the TinyMCE editor to the Lightning Rich Text Editor in OmniScripts and FlexCards, SkipUserProfileOnOSLoad improves OmniScript preview performance by hiding the userProfile node, and RetainDesignerSettingOnUpgrade prevents the designer from switching to standard on package upgrade. DocuSign integration requires DocuSignAccountId and DocuSignNamedCredential configuration records.","The standard designer is available by default for new users starting with Summer 2025 without requiring a managed package installation. Existing users on managed packages must first enable the OmniStudio license, install the latest package, migrate to standard runtime, and then the standard designer becomes available. Components created in the standard designer cannot be edited in the managed package designer, so creating new versions before switching is recommended."],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"Interaction config controls OmniScript runtime behavior"},{planet:"integration",desc:"Interaction config governs IP caching and execution policies"},{planet:"experience",desc:"Interaction config defines settings for Experience Cloud contexts"}]},
    {id:"cfg-autonumber",name:"Global Auto Number",icon:"\u{1F522}",desc:"Sequential identifier generation for OmniStudio business processes. Auto number definitions create unique, formatted identifiers like case numbers, application IDs, or reference codes that increment automatically. Administrators configure the prefix, suffix, number format, and starting value. Auto numbers are thread-safe and gap-free, suitable for compliance scenarios requiring sequential numbering. They can be invoked from OmniScripts and Integration Procedures through SetValues or dedicated actions.",tags:["OmniProcess"],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"Auto numbers generate sequential IDs within guided processes"}]},
    {id:"cfg-entitlements",name:"Usage-Based Entitlements",icon:"\u{1F4CA}",desc:"Execution metering that tracks OmniStudio component usage against licensed limits. Entitlement tracking monitors OmniScript launches, Integration Procedure executions, and Data Mapper operations, providing administrators with visibility into consumption patterns. Dashboard views show current usage against entitled limits with trend analysis. Threshold alerts notify administrators when usage approaches licensed maximums, enabling proactive capacity planning and license optimization.",tags:["OmniInteractionConfig"],connections:[{planet:"analytics",desc:"Entitlement data feeds into analytics dashboards"}]},
    {id:"cfg-esignature",name:"Electronic Signatures",icon:"\u{270D}",desc:"DocuSign template integration that enables legally binding electronic signature capture within OmniScript guided processes. Setup requires a DocuSign developer account, an OpenID Connect authentication provider, an OAuth 2.0 Named Credential, and Omni Interaction Configuration entries for DocuSignAccountId and DocuSignNamedCredential. The DocuSign login page must be added as a Trusted URL for Experience Cloud sites. Send-on-behalf functionality allows multiple users to initiate signing through shared credentials.",tags:["OmniElectronicSignatureTemplate"],docs:["DocuSign integration requires a multi-step setup: create a DocuSign developer account with an Integration Key, configure an OpenID Connect authentication provider in Salesforce, create an OAuth 2.0 Named Credential, and add two Omni Interaction Configuration entries (DocuSignAccountId with the API Account ID, and DocuSignNamedCredential with the credential name). For Experience Cloud sites, the DocuSign login page must be added as a Trusted URL with iframe content permissions.","Templates are prepared in DocuSign with custom fields (Text, Radio Button, Checkbox) that receive data from OmniScripts. Standard and prefill DocuSign fields are not supported for mapping. After creating templates in DocuSign, use the OmniStudio DocuSign Setup page (accessible from App Launcher) to fetch templates into Salesforce. Field mapping is handled through a Data Mapper Transform with the DocuSign output type.","The Send-on-behalf feature allows users to send or sign DocuSign documents through another user's credentials. This requires creating a DocuSignNamedCredential field on the User object and assigning the Send-on-behalf Named Credential to each user. When no Send-on-behalf credential is configured, DocuSign operations use the default admin user's credentials.","OmniScripts provide two DocuSign action elements: the DocuSign Envelope Action sends documents for signature via email, and the DocuSign Signature Action embeds the signing ceremony inline within the OmniScript. Both actions reference the signature template record and use the Data Mapper Transform output to populate template fields from OmniScript data. Make sure the connected Salesforce user and DocuSign user share the same email address and name."],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"E-signature actions are invoked from OmniScript steps"}]}
  ],
  dataFlow:["Administrator creates OmniInteractionConfig records with runtime settings","OmniScript or IP reads applicable configuration at execution time","Auto number definitions generate sequential identifiers on demand","Entitlement tracking records each component execution","Usage dashboards display consumption against licensed limits"],
  connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"Configuration settings control OmniScript runtime behavior"},{planet:"integration",desc:"Configuration governs Integration Procedure execution"},{planet:"analytics",desc:"Usage entitlements feed analytics reporting"},{planet:"testing",desc:"Configuration settings affect test execution context"},{planet:"experience",desc:"Configuration defines Experience Cloud-specific behavior"}]
},

experience: {
  packages: ['omnistudio'],
  name: "Experience Cloud",
  icon: "\u{1F310}",
  color: "#f87171",
  description: "Extends OmniStudio components to customer-facing and partner portals built on Salesforce Experience Cloud. OmniScripts and FlexCards can be placed directly on Experience Builder pages, providing the same guided process and contextual data card capabilities to external users. Authentication controls manage what data and processes are available to guest vs. authenticated users. Custom LWC extensions built for Experience Cloud contexts handle the unique styling, navigation, and security requirements of portal environments.",
  components: [
    {id:"ec-components",name:"Experience Builder Components",icon:"\u{1F9E9}",desc:"OmniStudio components surfaced as drag-and-drop elements in Experience Builder. On standard runtime, use the standard OmniScript and FlexCard components in Lightning App Builder and Experience Builder. On managed package runtime, use generated LWC components. OmniScripts can now be added to LWR (Lightning Web Runtime) sites in addition to Aura-based sites. For FlexCards on LWR sites, keep Managed Package Runtime enabled and use the generated LWC.",tags:["OmniProcess","OmniUiCard"],docs:["With standard runtime (Managed Package Runtime disabled), OmniScripts and FlexCards are added to Experience Cloud pages using the standard component available in Experience Builder. No separate LWC generation is needed since the standard component handles rendering directly. This approach provides instant activation and eliminates the compilation step. OmniScripts can be placed on both Aura-based Experience Cloud sites and LWR (Lightning Web Runtime) sites.","For FlexCards on LWR Experience sites, an important limitation exists: you must keep the Managed Package Runtime setting enabled and use the generated LWC component. The standard FlexCard component does not fully support LWR sites. This is a key consideration when planning your Experience Cloud architecture.","The Omniscript for Experience Builder component enables dynamic OmniScript loading from FlexCard actions. On an Aura-based site, you create a single page at the /lwcos URL and place the component on it, then all FlexCard OmniScript actions route through this shared page. On an LWR site, you select the Load Omniscript from URL checkbox instead of adding a component. This eliminates the need to create separate pages for each OmniScript.","SLDS Design Tokens applied to OmniScripts must include platform-specific versions for proper rendering. Aura-based sites use --lwc- prefixed tokens, LWR sites use --dxp-g- prefixed tokens, and Lightning pages use --slds-g- prefixed tokens. You can include all three token sets together, and each page type picks up only the tokens relevant to its platform."],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"OmniScripts are placed on Experience Cloud pages"},{planet:"flexcards",desc:"FlexCards are rendered on Experience Cloud pages"}]},
    {id:"ec-authentication",name:"Guest & Authenticated Access",icon:"\u{1F512}",desc:"Visibility and data access controls for OmniStudio components in portal environments. The ApexClassCheck security setting (enabled by default since February 2026) requires users to have explicit Apex class access for remote actions, preventing unauthorized access from guest user profiles. The EnableQueryWithFLS setting enforces field-level security for all queries in FlexCards. Administrators configure sharing rules, field-level security, and IP execution permissions for each access context.",tags:["OmniProcess"],docs:["Security in Experience Cloud environments is governed by three Omni Interaction Configuration flags. ApexClassCheck requires explicit Apex class access for any remote actions called from OmniScripts or FlexCards, preventing guest users from accessing classes through the Callable interface. EnforceDMFLSAndDataEncryption enforces object and field-level security for all Data Mappers, and users without View Encrypted Data permission cannot view encrypted fields. EnableQueryWithFLS enforces field-level security for SOQL and SOSL queries in FlexCards.","For guest access (unauthenticated users), publicly available APIs are enabled for the Site User profile based on the profile's Apex class access. The ApexClassCheck setting ensures the principle of least privilege by requiring explicit class permissions. Users who use Remote Actions in Integration Procedures must have access to the object and record they are invoking through the action, configurable at the profile, permission set, or permission set group level.","When Managed Package Runtime is disabled, the OmniStudio permission set license is required for end users to view standard FlexCards or OmniScripts on Lightning pages or Experience sites. Administrators also need the license to view and modify standard content in the designers. The permission set license controls access to OmniStudio features and must be assigned to all users who interact with OmniStudio components."],connections:[{planet:"config",desc:"Authentication settings reference interaction configuration"}]},
    {id:"ec-lwc",name:"Custom LWC Extensions",icon:"\u{1F4BB}",desc:"Lightning Web Components built specifically for Experience Cloud contexts where OmniStudio components need portal-specific customizations. These extensions handle scenarios like custom navigation after OmniScript completion, portal-specific styling overrides, integration with Experience Cloud session management, and custom header or footer components that wrap OmniStudio elements. They extend the standard OmniElement base class with additional portal-aware capabilities.",tags:["OmniProcess","OmniUiCard"],connections:[]}
  ],
  dataFlow:["Experience Builder page includes OmniScript or FlexCard components","Portal user accesses the page with guest or authenticated credentials","Authentication layer determines data visibility and process access","OmniScript or FlexCard renders with portal-appropriate styling","User interactions flow through the same backend as internal users"],
  connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"OmniScripts are embedded in Experience Cloud pages"},{planet:"flexcards",desc:"FlexCards are displayed on Experience Cloud pages"},{planet:"config",desc:"Experience Cloud uses interaction configuration for portal settings"}]
},

agentforce: {
  packages: ['omnistudio'],
  name: "Agentforce Integration",
  icon: "\u{1F916}",
  color: "#c084fc",
  description: "Connects OmniStudio components to Salesforce's Agentforce platform, enabling AI agents to leverage guided processes and contextual data displays. OmniScripts and Integration Procedures can be exposed as invocable agent actions, allowing agents to execute structured workflows on behalf of users. FlexCards serve as context surfaces that present relevant data to agents during conversations. Multi-component orchestration lets agents chain multiple OmniStudio components together to handle complex customer interactions that span data retrieval, process execution, and decision-making.",
  components: [
    {id:"af-actions",name:"Agent Actions",icon:"\u{26A1}",desc:"OmniScripts and Integration Procedures exposed as invocable actions for Agentforce agents. Administrators mark OmniStudio components as agent-callable and define the input parameters agents provide and the output data agents receive. Agents can launch guided processes, execute backend logic, and return results to the conversation context. Action definitions include natural language descriptions that help agents understand when and how to invoke each action appropriately.",tags:["OmniProcess"],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"OmniScripts are exposed as callable agent actions"},{planet:"integration",desc:"Integration Procedures execute as agent backend operations"}]},
    {id:"af-context",name:"Context Surfaces",icon:"\u{1F4C4}",desc:"FlexCards configured as context display surfaces within Agentforce agent interfaces. Context surfaces present relevant customer data, case details, and account information to agents during conversations, giving them the information needed to assist customers effectively. The same FlexCard definitions used in Lightning pages and Experience Cloud are reused as agent context, ensuring consistent data presentation across all channels.",tags:["OmniUiCard"],connections:[{planet:"flexcards",desc:"FlexCards provide contextual data display for agents"}]},
    {id:"af-orchestration",name:"Agent Orchestration",icon:"\u{1F3AF}",desc:"Multi-component workflows that chain OmniStudio elements together for complex agent interactions. Orchestration defines sequences where an agent retrieves data via FlexCards, executes business logic through Integration Procedures, and guides users through OmniScript processes, all within a single conversation flow. Branching logic lets agents choose different paths based on customer responses or data conditions, handling sophisticated service scenarios declaratively.",tags:["OmniProcess"],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"Orchestration chains OmniScript guided processes"},{planet:"flexcards",desc:"Orchestration uses FlexCards for agent data context"}]}
  ],
  dataFlow:["Agent receives a customer request during a conversation","Agent action invokes an OmniScript or Integration Procedure","Context surfaces display relevant customer data via FlexCards","Orchestration chains multiple components for complex workflows","Agent returns results and next steps to the conversation"],
  connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"OmniScripts are exposed as Agentforce actions"},{planet:"flexcards",desc:"FlexCards serve as context surfaces for agents"}]
},

analytics: {
  packages: ['omnistudio'],
  name: "OmniStudio Analytics",
  icon: "\u{1F4C8}",
  color: "#2dd4bf",
  description: "Tracking and measurement capabilities that provide visibility into how users interact with OmniStudio components. Tracking definitions capture events like step entries, element interactions, and process completions within OmniScripts. Engagement metrics aggregate this event data into actionable insights about completion rates, average time per step, and drop-off points. Analytics dashboards visualize these metrics through CRM Analytics, enabling administrators to identify process bottlenecks, optimize step design, and measure the business impact of guided experiences.",
  components: [
    {id:"oa-tracking",name:"Tracking Definitions",icon:"\u{1F4CD}",desc:"Configuration records that define which events are captured during OmniScript and FlexCard execution. OmniAnalytics supports both internal tracking (storing events in Salesforce) and third-party analytics integration with Google Analytics. Tracking definitions specify interaction types to monitor: step entries, element clicks, form submissions, error occurrences, and process completions. Ecommerce data can be attached to tracked events for transaction analysis.",tags:["OmniAnalyticsTrackingDef"],docs:["OmniAnalytics must be enabled before tracking data can be stored. Once enabled, tracking definitions specify what user interactions to capture and how to categorize them. Internal tracking stores event data in Salesforce for analysis through CRM Analytics dashboards. Third-party tracking integrates with Google Analytics by adding Google Analytics Trusted URLs and configuring the analytics tracking code on your OmniScripts.","Tracking supports multiple event types including step completion, element interaction, form submission, error occurrence, and process completion. Each tracking definition maps events to named categories and component types (OmniScript, FlexCard, or Integration Procedure). The tracking configuration is stored as JSON, allowing detailed control over which interactions generate events and what data is captured with each event.","For e-commerce scenarios, transaction data can be attached to tracked events by adding data-tracking attributes to OmniScript elements. This enables measuring the business impact of guided processes, such as tracking which OmniScript steps correlate with completed purchases or enrollment conversions. The data flows into Google Analytics e-commerce reports for transaction analysis alongside standard engagement metrics."],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"Tracking definitions capture events from OmniScript execution"}]},
    {id:"oa-metrics",name:"Engagement Metrics",icon:"\u{1F4CA}",desc:"Aggregated measurements derived from raw tracking event data. Engagement metrics calculate completion rates showing what percentage of users finish each OmniScript, average time per step revealing where users spend the most effort, drop-off analysis identifying where users abandon processes, and error frequency highlighting which elements cause the most validation failures. Metrics support filtering by date range, user segment, and OmniScript version for targeted analysis.",tags:["OmniAnalyticsTrackingDef"],connections:[]},
    {id:"oa-dashboards",name:"Analytics Dashboards",icon:"\u{1F4C9}",desc:"CRM Analytics visualization layer for OmniStudio tracking data. Pre-built dashboard templates display key OmniScript performance indicators including funnel views of step completion, heat maps of element interaction frequency, trend charts of usage over time, and comparison views across OmniScript versions. Custom dashboards can be built using the tracked event dataset, enabling administrators to answer specific questions about process efficiency and user behavior patterns.",tags:["OmniAnalyticsTrackingDef"],connections:[{planet:"config",desc:"Dashboards display entitlement usage and configuration metrics"}]}
  ],
  dataFlow:["Tracking definitions are enabled on target OmniScripts","User interactions generate tracking events during execution","Events are aggregated into engagement metrics","CRM Analytics dashboards visualize metrics and trends","Administrators identify bottlenecks and optimize process design"],
  connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"Analytics track OmniScript user interactions"},{planet:"config",desc:"Analytics report on entitlement usage and configuration"}]
},

testing: {
  packages: ['omnistudio'],
  name: "Testing & Quality",
  icon: "\u{2705}",
  color: "#a3e635",
  description: "Quality assurance tools for validating OmniStudio components during development and before deployment. The UTAM test framework provides page object models for automated browser testing of OmniScripts and FlexCards. The Design Assistant gives real-time feedback during authoring, flagging configuration issues, accessibility violations, and performance concerns before activation. Preview and Debug mode lets developers execute components with live data, inspect the JSON data model at each step, and test conditional logic branches without deploying to production.",
  components: [
    {id:"tq-utam",name:"UTAM Test Framework",icon:"\u{1F9EA}",desc:"UI Test Automation Model page objects for automated browser testing of OmniStudio components. UTAM provides pre-built page objects for OmniScript steps, input elements, FlexCard states, and action buttons. The testing workflow covers identifying the component to test, running the page generator to create page objects, writing end-to-end tests, running and debugging tests, and generating test reports. The framework integrates with WebDriverIO and Jest for CI/CD pipelines.",tags:["OmniProcess","OmniUiCard"],docs:["The UTAM testing workflow for FlexCards follows five steps: identify the FlexCard to test, run the UTAM Page Object Generator to create page objects from the FlexCard definition, write end-to-end test specs using the generated page objects, run the tests against a target Salesforce org, and generate test reports. Page objects abstract the FlexCard's DOM structure so tests interact with semantic elements rather than CSS selectors.","For OmniScripts, the UTAM workflow is similar but tests navigate through steps, fill in form data using the generated input element page objects, trigger actions, and validate outcomes at each step. The framework supports testing conditional visibility, formula calculations, and action results. Tests can verify that the correct FlexCard state renders based on data conditions, and that actions launch the expected OmniScripts.","Integration Procedure unit testing uses a separate mechanism through Test Procedures. Test Procedures are special Integration Procedures that invoke the target procedure with test data and use Assert actions to validate expected results. In the standard runtime, HTTP mocking is not available during test execution, so real HTTP calls occur. Apex test classes can also invoke Integration Procedures using the ConnectApi method for unit testing from code."],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"UTAM page objects automate testing of OmniScript flows"},{planet:"flexcards",desc:"UTAM page objects test FlexCard rendering and interactions"}]},
    {id:"tq-design-assistant",name:"Design Assistant",icon:"\u{1F4A1}",desc:"Real-time authoring feedback that analyzes OmniScript and FlexCard configurations as you build them. The Design Assistant flags common issues like missing required field validations, inaccessible color contrast ratios, elements without data bindings, and actions referencing non-existent Integration Procedures. Suggestions are categorized by severity (error, warning, info) and link to documentation explaining the best practice. This proactive quality check reduces the iteration cycles between building and testing.",tags:["OmniProcess","OmniUiCard"],connections:[{planet:"config",desc:"Design Assistant validates against interaction configuration rules"}]},
    {id:"tq-preview",name:"Preview & Debug",icon:"\u{1F50E}",desc:"Live preview mode that executes OmniScripts and FlexCards with real or sample data in the designer context. Preview renders the component exactly as users will see it, including conditional visibility, computed values, and action results. Debug mode adds a JSON panel showing the complete data model state, updated in real-time as you interact with the component. Step-through execution lets you test each step independently and inject test data at any point in the process flow.",tags:["OmniProcess","OmniUiCard"],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"Preview mode validates OmniScript behavior before activation"},{planet:"flexcards",desc:"Preview mode tests FlexCard rendering with live data"}]}
  ],
  dataFlow:["Developer builds OmniScript or FlexCard in the designer","Design Assistant provides real-time feedback on configuration quality","Preview mode renders the component with test data for validation","UTAM test suites automate regression testing of component behavior","Validated components are activated and packaged for deployment"],
  connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"Testing tools validate OmniScript configurations"},{planet:"flexcards",desc:"Testing tools validate FlexCard configurations"},{planet:"config",desc:"Testing respects interaction configuration context"}]
},

deployment: {
  packages: ['omnistudio'],
  name: "Deployment & Migration",
  icon: "\u{1F4E6}",
  color: "#94a3b8",
  description: "Tools for packaging, versioning, and migrating OmniStudio components across Salesforce environments. DataPacks bundle OmniScripts, FlexCards, Integration Procedures, Data Mappers, and their dependencies into portable export files that can be imported into target orgs. Version management controls the activation lifecycle of components, ensuring only one version is active at a time with clear rollback capabilities. Dependency resolution automatically identifies and includes all referenced components when building a DataPack, preventing partial deployments that would break component references in the target environment.",
  components: [
    {id:"dp-datapacks",name:"DataPack Export/Import",icon:"\u{1F4E5}",desc:"Two deployment paths for migrating OmniStudio components between orgs. On standard runtime with standard objects, Salesforce CLI is the recommended tool for consistent deployment across all Salesforce components. On managed package runtime, DataPacks bundle component definitions and dependencies into portable JSON files. You cannot deploy setup objects (FlexiPage, PermissionSet) and non-setup objects (OmniProcess, OmniUICard) together in the same deployment.",tags:["OmniDataPack"],docs:["For orgs on standard runtime with standard objects, Salesforce CLI is the recommended deployment tool. It handles OmniStudio components (OmniScripts, FlexCards, Integration Procedures, Data Mappers), other Salesforce components (Business Rules Engine), and metadata (FlexiPage, PermissionSet, LWCs). Salesforce CLI provides consistency, no learning curve for CLI users, and works across sandboxes, development orgs, and production orgs. The tool only works with standard objects in both source and target orgs.","DataPack export and import is used with the managed package designer and runtime. Export scans a selected component and its dependency tree, generating a structured JSON file. Import reads the file and creates or updates components in the target org. When exporting or importing OmniScripts, if you encounter Apex limit errors such as heap or CPU limits, reduce the DataPack size by unselecting dependencies and breaking into smaller packs with no more than 10 elements each.","The correct export order is: Data Mappers first, then Integration Procedures, then FlexCards and OmniScripts. This ensures that when components are imported in the target org, all referenced dependencies already exist. For Salesforce CLI exports, the SOQL query specifies which fields to include, and you must not include the isActive field on OmniProcess when exporting OmniScripts (importing with isActive=true causes failures).","Exporting and importing directly from the standard designer list page is not supported; you must use Salesforce CLI instead. The list page provides view, search, and filter capabilities but not DataPack export/import functionality. For managed package environments, the DataPack export is accessible from the component's menu in the designer, with options to save to the DataPack library or download locally."],connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"DataPacks export OmniScript definitions with all elements"},{planet:"flexcards",desc:"DataPacks export FlexCard definitions with states and actions"},{planet:"integration",desc:"DataPacks export Integration Procedure definitions"},{planet:"datamappers",desc:"DataPacks export Data Mapper definitions"}]},
    {id:"dp-versioning",name:"Version Management",icon:"\u{1F4CB}",desc:"Lifecycle controls for managing multiple versions of OmniStudio components. Each component supports multiple numbered versions with one active at a time. The standard designer provides a dedicated Manage Versions page for comparing versions and switching between them. The recommended limit is 10 FlexCard versions. When switching from managed package to standard designer, always create a new version first since components edited in the standard designer cannot be reopened in the managed package designer.",tags:["OmniProcess","OmniUiCard","OmniDataTransformation"],docs:["Version management ensures safe iteration on OmniStudio components. When you create a new version of a component, it receives the next sequential version number. Only one version can be active at a time for each unique identifier (Type/SubType/Language for OmniScripts, Type/SubType for IPs, Name/Author for FlexCards, InterfaceName for Data Mappers). Activating a new version automatically deactivates the current version.","The standard designer's Manage Versions page provides a centralized view of all versions for a component, making it easy to compare changes between versions and switch the active version. This page is accessible from the list view by clicking Versions or from the dropdown menu. The list view shows the last modified version of each record and supports up to 2,000 records with search, sort, and filter capabilities.","When transitioning from the managed package designer to the standard designer, the recommended approach is: turn on Managed Package Designer, create a new version (cloning the current active version), turn off Managed Package Designer, then open and validate the new version in the standard designer. This preserves the original version in case the standard designer reveals any compatibility issues. Test thoroughly in a sandbox before enabling in production.","Release updates from Salesforce push to Version 1 of standard OmniStudio components and are never editable. To modify standard components, create a new version, which you can then edit. Your created versions do not update with new releases from Salesforce, so you are responsible for incorporating any changes from newer versions that you want to adopt."],connections:[]},
    {id:"dp-dependencies",name:"Dependency Resolution",icon:"\u{1F517}",desc:"Automatic identification and inclusion of cross-component dependencies during DataPack export. When exporting an OmniScript, the resolver traces all referenced Integration Procedures, Data Mappers, FlexCards, child OmniScripts, and custom LWC references, including them in the export package. Dependency analysis also validates that all references will resolve in the target org, flagging missing components before deployment. This prevents broken references and ensures complete, functional migrations.",tags:["OmniDataPack"],connections:[]}
  ],
  dataFlow:["Administrator selects components for migration in DataPack export","Dependency resolution identifies all referenced components","DataPack bundles definitions into a portable JSON file","Import loads the DataPack into the target org with conflict detection","Version management activates the imported components"],
  connections:[{planet:"omniscripts",desc:"DataPacks package OmniScript definitions"},{planet:"flexcards",desc:"DataPacks package FlexCard definitions"},{planet:"integration",desc:"DataPacks package Integration Procedure definitions"},{planet:"datamappers",desc:"DataPacks package Data Mapper definitions"}]
}

};
